# GraphQL Query Complexity Risk Assessment

Ben's concern is legitimate but worth putting into concrete terms:

## Realistic Worst-Case Scenarios

**N+1 Problem Example:**
```graphql
query {
  customer {
    orders {
      items {
        product {
          reviews {
            author { profile }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
A customer with 100 orders × 10 items each could trigger thousands of database queries. This isn't a self-DDoS—it's a **slow, expensive query that starves other requests**.

**Unbounded Depth:**
```graphql
query {
  user {
    friends {
      friends {
        friends {
          friends { ... }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
With circular relationships (common in social graphs), depth limits are critical.

## Why This Matters for Your Portal

Your current REST BFF already orchestrates calls—you've *built* N+1 avoidance into business logic. GraphQL shifts that responsibility **to resolvers and query validation**. Without safeguards:

- A single poorly-written query could execute 500+ DB queries
- Performance degradation would be **non-obvious** (slow response, not an error)
- Harder to catch than REST because the same endpoint handles unlimited query shapes

## Practical Mitigation (Not Avoidance)

You won't "DDoS yourself" if you implement:

| Control | Why It Matters | Effort |
|---------|---|---|
| **Depth limits** (max 8-10 levels) | Prevents recursive traversal | Built-in (Apollo/graphql-core) |
| **Query complexity scoring** | Charge "points" per field; reject >threshold | Medium—requires tuning |
| **DataLoader/batching library** | Automatically coalesces DB queries | Medium—requires adoption |
| **Resolver timeout** (5-10s per resolver) | Kills pathological queries | Low—built-in |
| **Field-level auth checks** | Prevents accidental scope escalation | Medium—discipline-heavy |

